Question 10.Question:
The binding energy of helium 42He is

[Atomic mass of proton = 1.00783U, atomic mass of neutron = 1.00867U]
Question 10.Explanation:
The binding energy of a nucleus, is the work done or energy needed to separate completely the nucleons (protons and neutrons) apart.

Helium has 4 nucleons, 2 protons and 2 neutrons

2: H = 2 x 1.00783 = 2.01566

2: n = 2 x 1.00867 = 2.01734

∴ 2: H + 2:n = 4.03300u

But the helium nucleus has a mass of 4.00260u

∴ Binding energy = difference of nucleons and nucleus

= 4.03300U - 4.00260U = 0.03040U

Question 23.Question: In a gas experiment, if the volume of the gas is plotted against the reciprocal of the pressure, the unit of the slope of the resulting curve is
Question 23.Explanation:
If the volume of gas is plotted against the reciprocal of pressure, the slope will be given as

Slope = v/(1/p) = p x v

The unit of the slope will be;

P = f/a = Nm-2

v = m3

Slope = Nm-2 x m3 = Nm

The unit NM (Newton - Meter) is the practical unit of work, which is the product of force (N) and Displacement (M).

It should be noted that the practical unit of work is Newton-Meter, whereas its S.I unit is Joules, just as energy.
